LazyAdmin

Target IP: 10.10.41.118

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The default Apache2 webpage is displayed for this application. The source-code of this page does not reveal anything important. Time for a directory search.


Doing a directory search shows an interesting directory called /content.


Browsing to this directory shows the webpage above, and I did not find anything useful.


Doing another directory search against /content shows the entries above.


The /as shows the login webpage above. Trying default credentials like admin:admin did not work.


The /changelog.txt contains the application name and version. It seems like the target is running SweetRice CMS 1.5.0. However, browsing to http://10.10.41.118/content/inc/lastest.txt shows the target is running 1.5.1! Doing a Google search for exploits for this application version shows it is vulnerable.


I ran the command feroxbuster -u http://10.10.41.118/content/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-small.txt -x php,html,txt and got an interesting output above. It looks like the backup of the MySQL database for the web application is publicly available... Maybe this will contain the username and password?


And bingo! I opened the MySQL database file on my machine. The username manager and password hash 42f749ade7f9e195bf475f37a44cafcb is shown in the picture above highlighted in yellow.


After cracking the hash using crackstation, I obtained the password Password123. Now I have the credential manager:Password123. If this password has not been changed recently, I should be able to gain access to the CMS application.


And bingo! Using the credential at /as worked. Now I have access to the web application.

Exploitation


To exploit the machine, I successfully uploaded a PHP file using the Media Center feature in a zipped file format. I was able to access this web shell too after it got uploaded. To gain a reverse shell connection, I created a PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script in a zipped file format. Now I have a reverse shell connection on port 8443 after visiting the uploaded malicious file.

Privilege Escalation


The user itguy has saved their MySQL credential rice:randompass inside a file called mysql_login.txt.


There is an interesting file located called backup.pl. Is this a cronjob?


Is the admin using a reverse shell connection to his target machine? I have write privileges over this file too.


Running sudo -l shows the backup.pl can be executed.


I replaced the content of the copy.sh with my reverse shell.


And now I have a root shell. I started a listener on port 8444 and used the command sudo /usr/bin/perl /home/itguy/backup.pl to execute the backup Perl file.
